<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-573-099  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 573 099.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>DBMS  Nov 1990 v3 n12 p69(7).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Relational integrity. (building integrity constraints into Dbaselanguage applications)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kemm, Tom.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Applications maintaining database integrity use the command setsprovided by all Dbase languages.andP;  Integrity in a database involvestwo developing concepts: entity integrity and referentialintegrity.andP;  Entity integrity dictates that entity types arerepresented by specific .dbf files.andP;  They must each be unique.andO;Primary keys generated naturally, by the user, or assigned by thesystem must follow restraints to prevent loss of data.andO;Understanding referential integrity is important for the developerwhen changing the value of a primary key.andP;  Parent files requireconstraints for DELETing, and child files require constraints forAPPENDing.andP;  Relations between files need to be understood becauseEDIT constraints apply to both parent and child files.andP;  Dbasediffers from SQL-based databases with regards to security in thatit doesn't have dictionary-dependent constraints.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Relational Data BasesDesignNormalizationApplications Programming.andO;Feature:   illustrationprogram.andO;Caption:   Protecting keys. (program)Mnemonic names. (program)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>